               PCA and MSA. In addition, both groups code-switched in both PCA
               and MSA, with more code-switching in the MSA task than in the PCA
               task. Furthermore, an interaction with age revealed that young
               students code-switched more in MSA and older students
               code-switched more in PCA. Conclusions: It is suggested that the
               morphosyntactic abilities of DHH students are incomplete in both
               language varieties. Lack of spoken language input may negatively
               influence the acquisition of spoken language, which impacts
               further the acquisition of the standard language in diglossic
               contexts. Code-switching is explained as both due to lexical
               gaps, when occurring in MSA, and an effort to raise the register
               in PCA.},
