@article{Fowler1981-bw,
	abstract = {Examines some potential artifacts of design or execution of
               studies implying that central pattern masking may prevent
               awareness of perceptual products. Ss were 84 undergraduates.
               Three studies examined Ss' judgments of certain properties of
               masked words. Exps I and II replicated A. Marcel and K.
               Patterson's (1978) studies in demonstrating better-than-chance
               judgments about semantic properties of a word at target-mask
               intervals at which detection judgments and judgments of physical
               properties are at or near chance. However, a control``
               nonexperiment'' in which no words are presented before the mask
               yielded a similar outcome. Exp IV examined the relative semantic
               relatedness, as assessed by naive judges, of
               masked-target/response pairs of randomly associated words and
               responses and of the type obtained by A. Allport (1977). Judges
               did not distinguish the 2 kinds of word pairs. Despite these
               negative findings, a final pair of experiments replicated
               Marcel's demonstration that masked words, no less than unmasked
               words, facilitate lexical decisions concerning subsequently
