               (total N = 92) performance on the A trials was accurate. After
               the A trials, children watched as a toy was hidden at Location B,
               8 to 10 inches from Location A. In all experiments, children's
               searches after a 10-s delay were significantly biased in the
               direction of Location A. Furthermore, this bias toward Location A
               decreased with repeated trials to Location B, as well as when
               children completed fewer trials to Location A. Together, these
               data suggest that A-not-B-type errors are pervasive across tasks
               and development.},
